import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

sent_messages = df[df['from_id'].astype(str).str.contains(str(id))]
received_messages = df[df['to_id'].astype(str).str.contains(str(id))]

sent_messages_per_day = sent_messages.groupby(sent_messages['date'].dt.date).size()
received_messages_per_day = received_messages.groupby(received_messages['date'].dt.date).size()

min_date = min(sent_messages['date'].min(), received_messages['date'].min()).date()
max_date = max(sent_messages['date'].max(), received_messages['date'].max()).date()
date_range = pd.date_range(start=min_date, end=max_date)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plt.plot(sent_messages_per_day.index, sent_messages_per_day.values, label='Sent messages', color='red')
plt.plot(received_messages_per_day.index, received_messages_per_day.values, label='Received messages', color='blue')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of messages')
plt.title('Number of sent and received messages per day')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True)

plt.show()

df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'], errors='coerce')

df['year_month'] = df['date'].dt.to_period('M')

message_types_total = df['type'].value_counts()

import re

def process_id(to_id):
    try:
        return int(to_id)
    except ValueError:
        return None

top = df[df['from_id'].astype(str).str.contains(str(id), na=False)] \
                    .groupby('to_id') \
                    .size() \
                    .reset_index(name='message_count') \
                    .sort_values(by='message_count', ascending=False)

top['to_id'] = top['to_id'].apply(process_id)
top = top.dropna(subset=['to_id'])

valid = []

for _, row in top.iterrows():
    user_id = row['to_id']
    matching_record = df_meta[df_meta['dialog_id'] == user_id]

    valid.append({
        'name': matching_record.iloc[0]['name'],
        'message_count': row['message_count']
    })

    if len(valid) == 10:
        break

for item in valid:
    print(f"Name: {item['name']}, Message Count: {item['message_count']}")

top = df[df['to_id'].astype(str).str.contains(str(id), na=False)] \
                    .groupby('dialog_id') \
                    .size() \
                    .reset_index(name='message_count') \
                    .sort_values(by='message_count', ascending=False)

top = top.dropna(subset=['dialog_id'])

valid = []

for _, row in top.iterrows():
    dialog_id = row['dialog_id']
    matching_record = df_meta[df_meta['dialog_id'] == dialog_id]

    if not matching_record.empty:
        valid.append({
            'dialog_id': dialog_id,
            'name': matching_record.iloc[0]['name'],
            'message_count': row['message_count']
        })

    if len(valid) == 10:
        break

for item in valid:
    print(f"Name: {item['name']}, Message Count: {item['message_count']}")

Issues:

After some time original script was starting to send errors: Server sent a very old message with ID 7428741265596086273, ignoring Server sent a very old message with ID 7428741271254929409, ignoring Server sent a very old message with ID 7428741277087038465, ignoring Server sent a very old message with ID 7428741283355496449, ignoring Server sent a very old message with ID 7428741304305639425, ignoring Server sent a very old message with ID 7428741341416472577, ignoring

After which I had to restart script and all progress was lost.

So I upgraded script and make PR which you can see in this link: https://github.com/SanGreel/telegram-data-collection/pull/21 Here script looks for progress in output directory and continues from progress made there, so even if it fails, I dont need to start from scratch.. Additionally, it downloads dialogs in batches of 10,000 messages and saves.
